ction to ''Assault on Wall Street'' has been mainly negative, with one reviewer describing the film as \"Inexplicably tame\", However, it was better-received than most of Uwe Boll's productions.<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/assault_on_wall_street_2013/ |title=Assault On Wall Street |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |date= |accessdate=2014-02-15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|2368553}}\n\n{{Uwe Boll |state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:2013 direct-to-video films]]\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Canadian action thriller films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Great Recession]]\n[[Category:Canadian films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2008]]\n[[Category:Wall Street films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Uwe Boll]]\n[[Category:Financial thrillers]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n", "name_user": "Armyman74", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Assault_on_Wall_Street"}
{"title_page": "I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry", "text_new": "{{short description|2007 film by Dennis Dugan}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry\n| image          = Chuckandlarrymp.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Dennis Dugan]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Adam Sandler]]\n* [[Jack Giarraputo]]\n* [[Tom Shadyac]]\n* Michael Bostick\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* [[Barry Fanaro]]\n* [[Alexander Payne]]\n* [[Jim Taylor (writer)|Jim Taylor]]\n}}<!--The latter two are listed on the poster.!-->\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* Adam Sandler\n* [[Kevin James]]\n* [[Jessica Biel]]\n* [[Ving Rhames]]\n* [[Steve Buscemi]]\n* [[Dan Aykroyd]]\n* [[John Farley (actor)|John Farley]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Rupert Gregson-Williams]]\n| cinematography = [[Dean Semler]]\n| editing        = [[Jeff Gourson]] \n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Relativity Media]]\n* [[Shady Acres Entertainment]]\n* [[Happy Madison Productions]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2007|07|12|[[Universal City, California|Universal City]]|2007|07|20|United States}}\n| runtime        = 115 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 115:07--><ref>{{cite web|title=''I NOW PRONOUNCE YOU CHUCK & LARRY'' (12A)|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/i-now-pronounce-you-chuck-larry-2007-0|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=2007-07-24|accessdate=2013-07-16}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $85 million<ref name=\"boxoffice\"/>\n| gross          = $187.1 million<ref name=\"boxoffice\">{{cite web | url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=chuckandlarry.htm | title=I Now Pronounce You Chuck and Larry (2007) | publisher=Box Office Mojo | accessdate=June 10, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry''''' (also simply known as ''Chuck & Larry'') is a 2007 American [[comedy film]] directed by [[Dennis Dugan]]. It stars [[Adam Sandler]] and [[Kevin James]] as the title characters Chuck and Larry, respectively, two [[New York City Fire Department|New York City firefighters]] who pretend to be a gay couple in order to ensure one of their children can receive healthcare. The film was released in the United States on July 20, 2007, and was Sandler's first role in a [[Universal Pictures]] film since ''[[Bulletproof (1996 film)|Bulletproof]]'' in 1996.\n\n==Plot==\nChuck Levine, a womanizing bachelor, and Larry Valentine, a widower struggling to raise his two children, are two veteran [[New York City Fire Department|New York City firefighters]]. During a routine sweep of a burned building, a segment of floor collapses on Chuck, but Larry saves his life. Chuck vows to repay Larry in any way possible. Experiencing an epiphany from the incident, Larry tries to increase his life insurance policy. He finds out that a lapse in the paperwork after his wife's death keeps him from naming his children as primary beneficiaries. The representative from the insurance company suggests that Larry find a new spouse so he can name that person as his beneficiary. However, there is no woman in Larry's life that he loves or trusts.\n\nInspired by a newspaper article about domestic partnerships, Larry asks Chuck to enter a [[civil union]] with him. Although Chuck declines at first, he is reminded of his debt to Larry and finally agrees, entering a domestic partnership and becoming Larry's primary beneficiary in the event of his death. To their dismay, however, investigators arrive to inquire about their abrupt partnership, suspecting fraud. Chuck and Larry decide to enlist the help of lawyer Alex McDonough, who suggests they have a formal wedding ceremony to prove they are committed. The pair travel to [[Niagara Falls, Ontario]], [[Canada]] for a quick [[same-sex marriage]] at a [[wedding chapel]], and Chuck moves in with Larry and his children.\n\nAlex invites the couple to a gay benefit costume party. At the end of the evening, the partygoers are confronted by [[Homophobia|homophobic]] protesters. Chuck is provoked into punching their leader, and the incident is picked up by the local news. With their apparent homosexuality and marriage revealed, Chuck and Larry are heckled, and their fellow FDNY firefighters refuse to work with them. Their only ally is Fred G. Duncan, an angry, intimidating firefighter who reveals to Chuck that he is gay, and has not felt comfortable telling anyone.\n\nChuck becomes romantically interested in Alex after the two spend time together, but finds himself unable to get close to her because she thinks he is gay. During a heart-to-heart talk about relationships, the two spontaneously kiss, but Alex, still believing Chuck is gay and married, is shocked and immediately distances herself from Chuck. Meanwhile, city agent Clinton Fitzer arrives to investigate the couple, and the strain on both Larry and Chuck causes them to fight. Larry asserts that Chuck's constant absence to spend time with Alex is jeopardizing their ability to maintain the ruse of their relationship. Chuck tells Larry that he should stop refusing to move on from the death of his wife. Later that evening, a petition circulates to have Chuck and Larry thrown out of the firehouse. Upon discovering it, Larry confronts the crew about personal embarrassments on the job that Chuck and Larry helped them overcome. Afterwards, Chuck and Larry apologize to each other and reconcile their differences.\n\nEventually, numerous women publicly testify to having slept with Chuck in the recent past, and the couple is called into court to defend their marriage against charges of fraud. They are defended by Alex, and their fellow firefighters arrive in support, having realized all that Chuck and Larry have done for them over the years. Fitzer interrogates both men, and eventually demands the pair to kiss to prove that their relationship is physical. Before they do so, Chuck and Larry are interrupted by FDNY Captain Phineas J. Tucker, who reveals their marriage to be a sham and that they are both [[Heterosexuality|straight]]. He emphasizes that the situation reminded people not to be judgmental, and then offers to be arrested as well, since he knew about the false relationship but failed to report it. This prompts each of the other firefighters to claim a role in the wedding in a show of solidarity. Chuck, Larry, and the other firefighters are sent to jail, but they are quickly released after negotiating a deal to provide photos for an [[AIDS]] research benefit calendar, and Chuck and Larry keep their benefits.\n\nTwo months later, Fred and Alex's brother, Kevin, are married in Niagara Falls at the same chapel as Chuck and Larry. At the wedding party (which features musical guest [[Lance Bass]]), Larry moves on from the death of his wife and talks to a new woman, while Alex agrees to a dance with Chuck.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Adam Sandler]] as Charles Todd \"Chuck\" Levine\n* [[Kevin James]] as Lawrence Arthur \"Larry\" Valentine\n* [[Jessica Biel]] as Alex McDonough\n* [[Dan Aykroyd]] as Captain Phineas J. Tucker\n* [[Ving Rhames]] as Fred G. Duncan\n* [[Steve Buscemi]] as Clinton Fitzer\n* [[Peter Dante]] as Tony Paroni\n* [[Nicholas Turturro]] as Renaldo Pinera\n* [[Rachel Dratch]] as Sara Powers\n* [[Allen Covert]] as Steve\n* [[Richard Chamberlain (actor)|Richard Chamberlain]] as Councilman Banks\n* [[Nick Swardson]] as Kevin McDonough\n* [[John Farley (actor)|John Farley]] as Criminal (voice)\n* [[Lance Bass]] as Bandleader\n* Michael Marcanio as Eric Valentine\n* Shelby Adamowsky as Tori Valentine\n* [[Mary Pat Gleason]] as Teresa\n* [[Dave Matthews]] as Salesman\n* [[Blake Clark]] as Crazy homeless man\n* [[Dan Patrick]] as New York cop\n* [[Chandra West]] as \"Doctor Honey\"\n* [[Tila Tequila]] and [[Jamie Chung]] as [[Hooters]] girls\n* [[Dennis Dugan]] as Cab driver\n* [[Rob Corddry]] as Jim the minister\n* [[Jonathan Loughran]] as David Nootzie\n* [[Becky and Jessie O'Donohue]] as Donna and Darla\n* [[Robert Smigel]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Evans|first=Bradford|title=Which Movie Has the Most 'SNL' Cast Members In It?|date=18 July 2013|publisher=[[Splitsider]]|url=http://splitsider.com/2013/07/which-movie-has-the-most-snl-cast-members-in-it/|accessdate=16 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812011922/http://splitsider.com/2013/07/which-movie-has-the-most-snl-cast-members-in-it/|archive-date=August 12, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> as Mailman\n* [[David Spade]] (''uncredited'') as Transvestite groupie\n* [[Rob Schneider]] (''uncredited'') as Morris Takechi\n* Arne Starr (''uncredited'') as Court supporter\n* [[Jim Ford (actor)|Jim Ford]] (''uncredited'') as Criminal stuck in chimney\n\n==Production==\nProducer [[Tom Shadyac]] had planned this film as early as 1999. ''I Now Pronounce You Joe and Benny'', as the film was then titled, was announced as starring [[Nicolas Cage]] and [[Will Smith]] with Shadyac directing. In the official [[Trailer (promotion)|trailer]], the song \"Grace Kelly\" by British pop star, Mika, was included.<ref>{{Cite news | title = I, Nicolas Cage, take thee, Will Smith | newspaper = [[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] | page = 22 | date = 1999-05-25 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ImMEAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage | accessdate = 2010-08-02}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\n===Critical response===\n[[Rotten Tomatoes]], a [[review aggregator]], reports that 14% of 157 reviews surveyed critics gave the film a positive review; the average rating is 3.59/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"Whether by way of inept comedy or tasteless stereotypes, ''I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry'' falters on both levels.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/i_now_pronounce_you_chuck_and_larry/|title=I Now Pronounce You Chuck And Larry (2007)|accessdate=August 2, 2019|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 37 out of 100 based on 33 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.metacritic.com/movie/i-now-pronounce-you-chuck-larry |title = I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry Reviews |accessdate = 2016-12-12 |publisher=[[Flixster]] | work = [[Metacritic]] }}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web|url=https://m.cinemascore.com |archive-url=https://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20170916153548/https://m.cinemascore.com/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2017-09-16 |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com }}</ref>\n\n''[[USA Today]]'' called it \"a movie that gives marriage, [[homosexuality]], friendship, firefighters, children and nearly everything else a bad name.\"<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2007-07-19-chuck-and-larry_N.htm |title = 'Chuck and Larry': It's a marriage of bad taste, bad gags |accessdate = 2010-08-01 |publisher = [[USA Today]] | first=Claudia | last=Puig | date=2007-07-20}}</ref> The ''[[Wall St Journal]]'' calls it \"an insult to gays, straights, men, women, children, African-Americans, Asians, pastors, mailmen, insurance adjusters, firemen, doctors -- and fans of show music.\"<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118488195168472170 |title = 'Hairspray' Is Campy Fun, but Travolta Is a Drag  |accessdate = 2010-08-01 |publisher = [[Wall St Journal]] | first=Joanne | last=Kaufman | date=2007-07-20}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[New York Post]]'' called it not an insult to homosexuality but to comedy itself.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.nypost.com/seven/07202007/entertainment/movies/fdnwhy__movies_kyle_smith.htm |title = 'laughless comedy isn't a gay time' |access-date = 2010-08-01 |publisher = [[New York Post]] |first = Kyle |last = Smith |date = 2007-07-20 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080430142942/http://www.nypost.com/seven/07202007/entertainment/movies/fdnwhy__movies_kyle_smith.htm |archive-date = April 30, 2008 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''The [[Miami Herald]]'' was slightly less critical, calling the film \"funny in the juvenile, crass way we expect.\"<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.miamiherald.com/231/story/175223.html |title = 'Chuck & Larry' |accessdate = 2010-08-01 |publisher = [[The Miami Herald]] }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nNathan Lee from the ''[[Village Voice]]'' wrote a positive review, praising the film for being \"tremendously savvy in its stupid way\" and \"as eloquent as ''[[Brokeback Mountain]]'', and even more radical.\"<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.villagevoice.com/film/0729,lee,77246,20.html |title = 'Queer as Folk' |accessdate = 2010-08-01 |publisher = [[The Village Voice]] }}</ref> Controversial critic [[Armond White]] championed the film as \"a modern classic\" for its \"ultimate moral lesson\u2014that sexuality has absolutely nothing to do with who Chuck and Larry are as people\".<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.nypress.com/article-16861-bosom-buddies.html |title = 'Bossom Budies' |access-date = 2007-07-25 |publisher = [[New York Press]] |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120103224342/http://www.nypress.com/article-16861-bosom-buddies.html |archive-date = January 3, 2012 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Chuck & Larry'' grossed $34,233,750 and ranked #1 at the domestic box office in its opening weekend, higher than the other opening wide release that weekend, ''[[Hairspray (2007 film)|Hairspray]]'', and the previous weekend's #1 film, ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Weekend Box Office Results for July 20-22, 2007|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2007&wknd=29&p=.htm|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|date=2007-07-23|accessdate=2013-07-16}}</ref> By the end of its run, the film had grossed $120,059,556 domestically and $66,012,658 internationally for a worldwide total of $186,072,214.<ref name=\"boxoffice\"/>\n\n===Social responses and controversy===\nThe film was screened prior to release for the [[Gay & Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation]] (GLAAD). GLAAD representative Damon Romine told ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' magazine: \"The movie has some of the expected stereotypes, but in its own disarming way, it's a call for equality and respect\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20035285_20035331_20035169,00.html |title=I Now Pronounce You Chuck and Larry |publisher=Entertainment Weekly |date=2007-07-20 |accessdate=2011-03-25}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Alexander Payne]], the writer of an initial draft of the film, Sandler took many liberties with his screenplay, \"Sandler-izing\" the film, in his own words. At some point, he did not want his name attached to the project.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Peek at the Movie 'Chuck & Larry' Could Have Been|url=http://www.vulture.com/2007/07/a_peek_at_the_movie_chuck_larr.html|accessdate=October 11, 2016|work=Vulture|date=July 20, 2007}}</ref><ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/oscars/9013788/Oscars-2012-Alexander-Payne-on-The-Descendants.html</ref>\n\nCritics have also said the character played by [[Rob Schneider]] is a [[Racism in early American film|racist]] caricature by [[Whitewashing in film|whitewashing]], and he was also criticized for donning [[Portrayal of East Asians in Hollywood|Yellowface]].<ref>[http://www.afterelton.com/movies/2007/7/chuckandlarryreview afterelton.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070826172419/http://www.afterelton.com/movies/2007/7/chuckandlarryreview |date=August 26, 2007 }} ''Review of \"I Now Pronounce You Chuck and Larry\"''</ref>\n\nIn November 2007, the producers of the Australian film ''[[Strange Bedfellows (2004 film)|Strange Bedfellows]]'' initiated legal action against [[Universal Studios]] for copyright violation.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/news/film/filmmakers-take-on-hollywood-over-comedy-copy/2007/11/23/1195753303752.html Filmmakers take on Hollywood over comedy 'copy' - Film - Entertainment]</ref> ''Strange Bedfellows'', was released three years before. In comparison, the films have 100 similar plot points. Both movie plots deal with two firemen, who pretend to be a gay couple for financial reasons, are investigated, and then have to deal with the situation with their friends and community. The suit was withdrawn in April 2008 after the producers of ''Strange Bedfellows'' received an early draft of ''Chuck & Larry'' that predated their film, and they were satisfied that they had not been plagiarized.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/film/strange-fluke-not-plagiarism/2008/04/06/1207420193700.html |title=Strange fluke, not plagiarism - Film - Entertainment |newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald |date=2008-04-06 |accessdate=2011-03-25}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, a member of Chicago's city council cited the film during an argument over a city plan to set aside contracts for gay and transgender owned businesses. Alderman Walter Burnett said, \u201cI think about that movie about the two firemen where they were faking like they were gay\u2026 to get benefits. That\u2019s a concern of mine. How do you distinguish that?\u201d <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lgbtqnation.com/2020/01/democrat-cites-now-pronounce-chuck-larry-reason-oppose-lgbtq-measure/ |title=Democrat cites I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry as a reason to oppose LGBTQ measure |newspaper=LGBTQ Nation |date=2020-01-15 |accessdate=2020-01-15}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nThe film was released on DVD and Blu-Ray on November 6, 2007.\n\n==Accolades==\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\nThe film received eight [[28th Golden Raspberry Awards|Golden Raspberry Award]] nominations including [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Picture|Worst Picture]], [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actor|Worst Actor]] (Adam Sandler), [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actor|Worst Supporting Actor]] (both Kevin James and Rob Schneider), [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress|Worst Supporting Actress]] (Jessica Biel), [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director|Worst Director]] (Dennis Dugan), [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screenplay|Worst Screenplay]] and [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screen Couple/Ensemble|Worst Screen Couple]] (Adam Sandler with either Kevin James or Jessica Biel), but did not win any.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Boston marriage]]\n*[[Mariage blanc]]\n*[[Marriage of convenience]]\n*[[Non-sexual same-sex marriage]]\n*[[Sham marriage]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|I Now Pronounce You Chuck and Larry}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.chuckandlarry.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|0762107|I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry}}\n* {{mojo title|chuckandlarry|I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|i_now_pronounce_you_chuck_and_larry|I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry}}\n* {{metacritic film|i-now-pronounce-you-chuck-larry|I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry}}\n\n{{Dennis Dugan}}\n{{Happy Madison Productions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:I Now Pronounce You Chuck And Larry}}\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:2000s buddy films]]\n[[Category:2000s screwball comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:American buddy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:American screwball comedy films]]\n[[Category:American sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about weddings]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films set in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Films about firefighting]]\n[[Category:Happy Madison Productions films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:Niagara Falls in fiction]]\n[[Category:Niagara Falls, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Same-sex marriage in film]]\n[[Category:Relativity Media films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Dennis Dugan]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Adam Sandler]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Jack Giarraputo]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Rupert Gregson-Williams]]\n[[Category:Films involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Alexander Payne]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jim Taylor (writer)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2007 film by Dennis Dugan}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry\n| image          = Chuckandlarrymp.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Dennis Dugan]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Adam Sandler]]\n* [[Jack Giarraputo]]\n* [[Tom Shadyac]]\n* Michael Bostick\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* [[Barry Fanaro]]\n* [[Alexander Payne]]\n* [[Jim Taylor (writer)|Jim Taylor]]\n}}<!--The latter two are listed on the poster.!-->\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* Adam Sandler\n* [[Kevin James]]\n* [[Jessica Biel]]\n* [[Ving Rhames]]\n* [[Steve Buscemi]]\n* [[Dan Aykroyd]]\n* [[John Farley (actor)|John Farley]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Rupert Gregson-Williams]]\n| cinematography = [[Dean Semler]]\n| editing        = [[Jeff Gourson]] \n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Relativity Media]]\n* [[Shady Acres Entertainment]]\n* [[Happy Madison Productions]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2007|07|12|[[Universal City, California|Universal City]]|2007|07|20|United States}}\n| runtime        = 115 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 115:07--><ref>{{cite web|title=''I NOW PRONOUNCE YOU CHUCK & LARRY'' (12A)|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/i-now-pronounce-you-chuck-larry-2007-0|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=2007-07-24|accessdate=2013-07-16}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $85 million<ref name=\"boxoffice\"/>\n| gross          = $187.1 million<ref name=\"boxoffice\">{{cite web | url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=chuckandlarry.htm | title=I Now Pronounce You Chuck and Larry (2007) | publisher=Box Office Mojo | accessdate=June 10, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry''''' (also simply known as ''Chuck & Larry'') is a 2007 American [[comedy film]] directed by [[Dennis Dugan]]. It stars [[Adam Sandler]] and [[Kevin James]] as the title characters Chuck and Larry, respectively, two [[New York City Fire Department|New York City firefighters]] who pretend to be a gay couple in order to ensure one of their children can receive healthcare. The film was released in the United States on July 20, 2007, and was Sandler's first role in a [[Universal Pictures]] film since ''[[Bulletproof (1996 film)|Bulletproof]]'' in 1996.\n\n==Plot==\nChuck Levine, a womanizing bachelor, and Larry Valentine, a widower struggling to raise his two children, are two veteran [[New York City Fire Department|New York City firefighters]]. During a routine sweep of a burned building, a segment of floor collapses on Chuck, but Larry saves his life. Chuck vows to repay Larry in any way possible. Experiencing an epiphany from the incident, Larry tries to increase his life insurance policy. He finds out that a lapse in the paperwork after his wife's death keeps him from naming his children as primary beneficiaries. The representative from the insurance company suggests that Larry find a new spouse so he can name that person as his beneficiary. However, there is no woman in Larry's life that he loves or trusts.\n\nInspired by a newspaper article about domestic partnerships, Larry asks Chuck to enter a [[civil union]] with him. Although Chuck declines at first, he is reminded of his debt to Larry and finally agrees, entering a domestic partnership and becoming Larry's primary beneficiary in the event of his death. To their dismay, however, investigators arrive to inquire about their abrupt partnership, suspecting fraud. Chuck and Larry decide to enlist the help of lawyer Alex McDonough, who suggests they have a formal wedding ceremony to prove they are committed. The pair travel to [[Niagara Falls, Ontario]], [[Canada]] for a quick [[same-sex marriage]] at a [[wedding chapel]], and Chuck moves in with Larry and his children.\n\nAlex invites the couple to a gay benefit costume party. At the end of the evening, the partygoers are confronted by [[Homophobia|homophobic]] protesters. Chuck is provoked into punching their leader, and the incident is picked up by the local news. With their apparent homosexuality and marriage revealed, Chuck and Larry are heckled, and their fellow FDNY firefighters refuse to work with them. Their only ally is Fred G. Duncan, an angry, intimidating firefighter who reveals to Chuck that he is gay, and has not felt comfortable telling anyone.\n\nChuck becomes romantically interested in Alex after the two spend time together, but finds himself unable to get close to her because she thinks he is gay. During a heart-to-heart talk about relationships, the two spontaneously kiss, but Alex, still believing Chuck is gay and married, is shocked and immediately distances herself from Chuck. Meanwhile, city agent Clinton Fitzer arrives to investigate the couple, and the strain on both Larry and Chuck causes them to fight. Larry asserts that Chuck's constant absence to spend time with Alex is jeopardizing their ability to maintain the ruse of their relationship. Chuck tells Larry that he should stop refusing to move on from the death of his wife. Later that evening, a petition circulates to have Chuck and Larry thrown out of the firehouse. Upon discovering it, Larry confronts the crew about personal embarrassments on the job that Chuck and Larry helped them overcome. Afterwards, Chuck and Larry apologize to each other and reconcile their differences.\n\nEventually, numerous women publicly testify to having slept with Chuck in the recent past, and the couple is called into court to defend their marriage against charges of fraud. They are defended by Alex, and their fellow firefighters arrive in support, having realized all that Chuck and Larry have done for them over the years. Fitzer interrogates both men, and eventually demands the pair to kiss to prove that their relationship is physical. Before they do so, Chuck and Larry are interrupted by FDNY Captain Phineas J. Tucker, who reveals their marriage to be a sham and that they are both [[Heterosexuality|straight]]. He emphasizes that the situation reminded people not to be judgmental, and then offers to be arrested as well, since he knew about the false relationship but failed to report it. This prompts each of the other firefighters to claim a role in the wedding in a show of solidarity. Chuck, Larry, and the other firefighters are sent to jail, but they are quickly released after negotiating a deal to provide photos for an [[AIDS]] research benefit calendar, and Chuck and Larry keep their benefits.\n\nTwo months later, Fred and Alex's brother, Kevin, are married in Niagara Falls at the same chapel as Chuck and Larry. At the wedding party (which features musical guest [[Lance Bass]]), Larry moves on from the death of his wife and talks to a new woman, while Alex agrees to a dance with Chuck.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Adam Sandler]] as Charles Todd \"Chuck\" Levine\n* [[Kevin James]] as Lawrence Arthur \"Larry\" Valentine\n* [[Jessica Biel]] as Alex McDonough\n* [[Dan Aykroyd]] as Captain Phineas J. Tucker\n* [[Ving Rhames]] as Fred G. Duncan\n* [[Steve Buscemi]] as Clinton Fitzer\n* [[Peter Dante]] as Tony Paroni\n* [[Nicholas Turturro]] as Renaldo Pinera\n* [[Rachel Dratch]] as Sara Powers\n* [[Allen Covert]] as Steve\n* [[Richard Chamberlain (actor)|Richard Chamberlain]] as Councilman Banks\n* [[Nick Swardson]] as Kevin McDonough\n* [[John Farley (actor)|John Farley]] as Criminal (voice)\n* [[Lance Bass]] as Bandleader\n* Cole Morgen as Eric Valentine\n* Shelby Adamowsky as Tori Valentine\n* [[Mary Pat Gleason]] as Teresa\n* [[Dave Matthews]] as Salesman\n* [[Blake Clark]] as Crazy homeless man\n* [[Dan Patrick]] as New York cop\n* [[Chandra West]] as \"Doctor Honey\"\n* [[Tila Tequila]] and [[Jamie Chung]] as [[Hooters]] girls\n* [[Dennis Dugan]] as Cab driver\n* [[Rob Corddry]] as Jim the minister\n* [[Jonathan Loughran]] as David Nootzie\n* [[Becky and Jessie O'Donohue]] as Donna and Darla\n* [[Robert Smigel]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Evans|first=Bradford|title=Which Movie Has the Most 'SNL' Cast Members In It?|date=18 July 2013|publisher=[[Splitsider]]|url=http://splitsider.com/2013/07/which-movie-has-the-most-snl-cast-members-in-it/|accessdate=16 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812011922/http://splitsider.com/2013/07/which-movie-has-the-most-snl-cast-members-in-it/|archive-date=August 12, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> as Mailman\n* [[David Spade]] (''uncredited'') as Transvestite groupie\n* [[Rob Schneider]] (''uncredited'') as Morris Takechi\n* Arne Starr (''uncredited'') as Court supporter\n* [[Jim Ford (actor)|Jim Ford]] (''uncredited'') as Criminal stuck in chimney\n\n==Production==\nProducer [[Tom Shadyac]] had planned this film as early as 1999. ''I Now Pronounce You Joe and Benny'', as the film was then titled, was announced as starring [[Nicolas Cage]] and [[Will Smith]] with Shadyac directing. In the official [[Trailer (promotion)|trailer]], the song \"Grace Kelly\" by British pop star, Mika, was included.<ref>{{Cite news | title = I, Nicolas Cage, take thee, Will Smith | newspaper = [[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] | page = 22 | date = 1999-05-25 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ImMEAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage | accessdate = 2010-08-02}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\n===Critical response===\n[[Rotten Tomatoes]], a [[review aggregator]], reports that 14% of 157 reviews surveyed critics gave the film a positive review; the average rating is 3.59/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"Whether by way of inept comedy or tasteless stereotypes, ''I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry'' falters on both levels.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/i_now_pronounce_you_chuck_and_larry/|title=I Now Pronounce You Chuck And Larry (2007)|accessdate=August 2, 2019|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 37 out of 100 based on 33 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.metacritic.com/movie/i-now-pronounce-you-chuck-larry |title = I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry Reviews |accessdate = 2016-12-12 |publisher=[[Flixster]] | work = [[Metacritic]] }}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web|url=https://m.cinemascore.com |archive-url=https://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20170916153548/https://m.cinemascore.com/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2017-09-16 |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com }}</ref>\n\n''[[USA Today]]'' called it \"a movie that gives marriage, [[homosexuality]], friendship, firefighters, children and nearly everything else a bad name.\"<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2007-07-19-chuck-and-larry_N.htm |title = 'Chuck and Larry': It's a marriage of bad taste, bad gags |accessdate = 2010-08-01 |publisher = [[USA Today]] | first=Claudia | last=Puig | date=2007-07-20}}</ref> The ''[[Wall St Journal]]'' calls it \"an insult to gays, straights, men, women, children, African-Americans, Asians, pastors, mailmen, insurance adjusters, firemen, doctors -- and fans of show music.\"<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118488195168472170 |title = 'Hairspray' Is Campy Fun, but Travolta Is a Drag  |accessdate = 2010-08-01 |publisher = [[Wall St Journal]] | first=Joanne | last=Kaufman | date=2007-07-20}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[New York Post]]'' called it not an insult to homosexuality but to comedy itself.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.nypost.com/seven/07202007/entertainment/movies/fdnwhy__movies_kyle_smith.htm |title = 'laughless comedy isn't a gay time' |access-date = 2010-08-01 |publisher = [[New York Post]] |first = Kyle |last = Smith |date = 2007-07-20 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080430142942/http://www.nypost.com/seven/07202007/entertainment/movies/fdnwhy__movies_kyle_smith.htm |archive-date = April 30, 2008 |df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''The [[Miami Herald]]'' was slightly less critical, calling the film \"funny in the juvenile, crass way we expect.\"<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.miamiherald.com/231/story/175223.html |title = 'Chuck & Larry' |accessdate = 2010-08-01 |publisher = [[The Miami Herald]] }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nNathan Lee from the ''[[Village Voice]]'' wrote a positive review, praising the film for being \"tremendously savvy in its stupid way\" and \"as eloquent as ''[[Brokeback Mountain]]'', and even more radical.\"<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.villagevoice.com/film/0729,lee,77246,20.html |title = 'Queer as Folk' |accessdate = 2010-08-01 |publisher = [[The Village Voice]] }}</ref> Controversial critic [[Armond White]] championed the film as \"a modern classic\" for its \"ultimate moral lesson\u2014that sexuality has absolutely nothing to do with who Chuck and Larry are as people\".<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.nypress.com/article-16861-bosom-buddies.html |title = 'Bossom Budies' |access-date = 2007-07-25 |publisher = [[New York Press]] |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120103224342/http://www.nypress.com/article-16861-bosom-buddies.html |archive-date = January 3, 2012 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Chuck & Larry'' grossed $34,233,750 and ranked #1 at the domestic box office in its opening weekend, higher than the other opening wide release that weekend, ''[[Hairspray (2007 film)|Hairspray]]'', and the previous weekend's #1 film, ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Weekend Box Office Results for July 20-22, 2007|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2007&wknd=29&p=.htm|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|date=2007-07-23|accessdate=2013-07-16}}</ref> By the end of its run, the film had grossed $120,059,556 domestically and $66,012,658 internationally for a worldwide total of $186,072,214.<ref name=\"boxoffice\"/>\n\n===Social responses and controversy===\nThe film was screened prior to release for the [[Gay & Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation]] (GLAAD). GLAAD representative Damon Romine told ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' magazine: \"The movie has some of the expected stereotypes, but in its own disarming way, it's a call for equality and respect\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20035285_20035331_20035169,00.html |title=I Now Pronounce You Chuck and Larry |publisher=Entertainment Weekly |date=2007-07-20 |accessdate=2011-03-25}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Alexander Payne]], the writer of an initial draft of the film, Sandler took many liberties with his screenplay, \"Sandler-izing\" the film, in his own words. At some point, he did not want his name attached to the project.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Peek at the Movie 'Chuck & Larry' Could Have Been|url=http://www.vulture.com/2007/07/a_peek_at_the_movie_chuck_larr.html|accessdate=October 11, 2016|work=Vulture|date=July 20, 2007}}</ref><ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/oscars/9013788/Oscars-2012-Alexander-Payne-on-The-Descendants.html</ref>\n\nCritics have also said the character played by [[Rob Schneider]] is a [[Racism in early American film|racist]] caricature by [[Whitewashing in film|whitewashing]], and he was also criticized for donning [[Portrayal of East Asians in Hollywood|Yellowface]].<ref>[http://www.afterelton.com/movies/2007/7/chuckandlarryreview afterelton.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070826172419/http://www.afterelton.com/movies/2007/7/chuckandlarryreview |date=August 26, 2007 }} ''Review of \"I Now Pronounce You Chuck and Larry\"''</ref>\n\nIn November 2007, the producers of the Australian film ''[[Strange Bedfellows (2004 film)|Strange Bedfellows]]'' initiated legal action against [[Universal Studios]] for copyright violation.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/news/film/filmmakers-take-on-hollywood-over-comedy-copy/2007/11/23/1195753303752.html Filmmakers take on Hollywood over comedy 'copy' - Film - Entertainment]</ref> ''Strange Bedfellows'', was released three years before. In comparison, the films have 100 similar plot points. Both movie plots deal with two firemen, who pretend to be a gay couple for financial reasons, are investigated, and then have to deal with the situation with their friends and community. The suit was withdrawn in April 2008 after the producers of ''Strange Bedfellows'' received an early draft of ''Chuck & Larry'' that predated their film, and they were satisfied that they had not been plagiarized.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/film/strange-fluke-not-plagiarism/2008/04/06/1207420193700.html |title=Strange fluke, not plagiarism - Film - Entertainment |newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald |date=2008-04-06 |accessdate=2011-03-25}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, a member of Chicago's city council cited the film during an argument over a city plan to set aside contracts for gay and transgender owned businesses. Alderman Walter Burnett said, \u201cI think about that movie about the two firemen where they were faking like they were gay\u2026 to get benefits. That\u2019s a concern of mine. How do you distinguish that?\u201d <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lgbtqnation.com/2020/01/democrat-cites-now-pronounce-chuck-larry-reason-oppose-lgbtq-measure/ |title=Democrat cites I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry as a reason to oppose LGBTQ measure |newspaper=LGBTQ Nation |date=2020-01-15 |accessdate=2020-01-15}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nThe film was released on DVD and Blu-Ray on November 6, 2007.\n\n==Accolades==\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\nThe film received eight [[28th Golden Raspberry Awards|Golden Raspberry Award]] nominations including [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Picture|Worst Picture]], [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actor|Worst Actor]] (Adam Sandler), [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actor|Worst Supporting Actor]] (both Kevin James and Rob Schneider), [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress|Worst Supporting Actress]] (Jessica Biel), [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director|Worst Director]] (Dennis Dugan), [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screenplay|Worst Screenplay]] and [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screen Couple/Ensemble|Worst Screen Couple]] (Adam Sandler with either Kevin James or Jessica Biel), but did not win any.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Boston marriage]]\n*[[Mariage blanc]]\n*[[Marriage of convenience]]\n*[[Non-sexual same-sex marriage]]\n*[[Sham marriage]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|I Now Pronounce You Chuck and Larry}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.chuckandlarry.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|0762107|I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry}}\n* {{mojo title|chuckandlarry|I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|i_now_pronounce_you_chuck_and_larry|I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry}}\n* {{metacritic film|i-now-pronounce-you-chuck-larry|I Now Pronounce You Chuck & Larry}}\n\n{{Dennis Dugan}}\n{{Happy Madison Productions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:I Now Pronounce You Chuck And Larry}}\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:2000s buddy films]]\n[[Category:2000s screwball comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:American buddy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:American screwball comedy films]]\n[[Category:American sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about weddings]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films set in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Films about firefighting]]\n[[Category:Happy Madison Productions films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:Niagara Falls in fiction]]\n[[Category:Niagara Falls, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Same-sex marriage in film]]\n[[Category:Relativity Media films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Dennis Dugan]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Adam Sandler]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Jack Giarraputo]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Rupert Gregson-Williams]]\n[[Category:Films involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Alexander Payne]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jim Taylor (writer)]]\n", "name_user": "2600:8801:1c80:2ed4:2d5a:72f5:7374:b8a4", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCast)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Now_Pronounce_You_Chuck_%26_Larry"}
{"title_page": "I See You (2019 film)", "text_new": "{{missing information|the film's theatrical/home media releases|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = I See You\n| image          = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = U.S. Theatrical Poster\n| director       = Adam Randall\n| producers      = Matt Waldeck\n| writers        = [[Devon Graye]]\n| story          = \n| starring       = [[Helen Hunt]]<br/>[[Jon Tenney]]<br/>[[Judah Lewis]]<br/>[[Owen Teague]]<br/>[[Libe Barer]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Philipp Blaubach\n| editing        = Jeff Castelluccio\n| studio         = Bankside Films<br>Head Gear Films<br>Quickfire Films<br>Zodiac Features\n| distributor    = [[Saban Films]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|03|11|[[South by Southwest]]|2019|12|6|United States}}\n| runtime        = 96 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''I See You''''' is a 2019 American thriller-horror film written by [[Devon Graye]], directed by [[Adam Randall]], produced by [[Matt Waldeck]] and starring [[Helen Hunt]], [[Jon Tenney]], [[Judah Lewis]], [[Owen Teague]] and [[Libe Barer]].<ref>{{Citation|title=I See You|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6079516/|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Miska|first=Brad|title=Helen Hunt Shoots Off An Intense Look In First Shot From \u2018I See You\u2019|date=14 May 2018|publisher=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3498709/helen-hunt-shoots-off-intense-look-first-shot-see/|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|title=Helen Hunt To Star In Horror-Thriller \u2018I See You\u2019|date=7 June 2017|magazine=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/helen-hunt-i-see-you-horror-movie-casting-1202108848/|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=McNary|first=Dave|title=Helen Hunt to Star in Horror-Thriller \u2018I See You\u2019|date=7 June 2017|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/helen-hunt-i-see-you-1202456735/|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref> It follows a suburban family beset by unexplainable events that may be linked to the recent disappearance of a young boy.\n\n==Plot==\nTen-year-old Justin Whitter is abducted while riding his bicycle through a local park. Greg Harper (Jon Tenney) is made lead detective on the case. Evidence in the form of a green pocket knife is found connecting this case to a previous series of abductions which resulted in the conviction of another man many years prior. Harper's family is shown to be going through its own troubles based on an affair his wife, Jackie ([[Helen Hunt]]), had been in engaged in. Their son, Connor (Judah Lewis), is very resentful toward his mother because of the affair.\n\nMysterious events begin plaguing the house; all the silverware and Jackie's favorite coffee mug go missing, and a window repairman is let in by someone inside the house while the family is away. Jackie's former lover, Todd (Sam Trammel), arrives at the house, and is injured when Jackie's coffee mug falls from the roof and hits him on the head. Jackie hides him in the basement so she can take Connor to school. While looking around the basement, Todd is hit over the head by an unknown assailant and Jackie comes home to find him dead. She panics and assumes that Connor has killed Todd. She and Greg take the body to a wooded area and bury his body, hoping to give Connor an alibi.\n\nConnor is shown footage of \"phrogging\", a practice in which people hide in a house unbeknownst to the owners and move around freely when alone in the house, and is attacked by a figure in a frog mask. Greg and Jackie find Connor tied up in the bathtub with a green pocket knife nearby. Jackie drives Connor to the hospital while Greg searches the house and is attacked with an axe by the frog-masked figure.\n\nThe film then jumps back in time and reveals that the mysterious happenings in the house are caused by two people, Mindy (Libe Barer) and Alec (Owen Teague), who have been \"phrogging\" in the Harper home. Mindy, an experienced phrogger, tries to keep a very low profile so that she never gets caught, while novice phrogger Alec decides he wants to make the family believe they are going insane. Every mysterious occurrence in the film is shown to have been caused by Alec, including the missing silverware and Todd's incapacitation. However, while Todd is in the basement, Mindy witnesses Greg killing him and goes to alert Alec, only to see him incapacitating Connor in the bathtub. She argues with Alec, who mistakenly pushes her down the stairs and knocks her out. Alec hides her in Greg's car. Greg and Jackie find Connor in the bathtub and Jackie takes him to the hospital. After Jackie leaves, Greg takes his own car, taking Mindy with him without realizing it.\n\nMindy awakens in the car and finds a bag of green pocket knives and Justin Whitter's shirt, realizing that Greg is the kidnapper. Greg parks in the forest, where Mindy finds an old trailer with all the abducted children trapped in make-shift closets. As Mindy tries to free them, Greg ambushes her and returns to the house with her. He forces her to stand up before shooting her dead, then doctors the scene to make it appear that she attacked him and he killed her in self-defense. Alec gets Greg's attention and attacks him with an axe. Greg knocks Alec out, but he stirs and takes Greg's gun. Revealing that he knows Greg's identity as the kidnapper, Alec reveals his face to Greg, who appears to recognize him. Greg attempts to explain himself, but Alec makes it clear that he does not care before shooting and killing Greg. Greg's partner Spitzky arrives and shoots Alec, but Alec survives and the two recognize each other. \n\nThe boys are rescued from the trailer and Greg's bags containing the police evidence are found. Jackie and Connor arrive to find their home has become swarmed with police cars and ambulances. Flashbacks are shown of a younger Alec and a friend encountering Greg, who hands Alec a green pocket knife, as in the present day Alec - a previous victim of Greg's - is carried into an ambulance.  This explains why, earlier in the film, that Alec picked that particular house to phrog and begged Mindy to come with him.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Helen Hunt]] as Jackie Harper\n*[[Jon Tenney]] as Greg Harper\n*[[Judah Lewis]] as Connor Harper\n*[[Owen Teague]] as Alec\n*[[Libe Barer]] as Mindy\n*[[Gregory Alan Williams]] as Spitzky\n*[[Erika Alexander]] as Lieutenant Moriah Davis\n*Allison King as Officer Grace Caleb\n*Adam Kern as Window Repairman\n*[[Sam Trammell]] as Todd\n*Jeremy Gladen as Tommy Braun\n*Teri Clark as Mrs. Braun\n*[[Nicole Forester]] as Mrs. Whitter\n\n==Production==\n{{expand section|date=December 2019}}\nPrincipal photography took place in May 2018 in [[Chagrin Falls]], [[Cleveland]] and [[Lakewood, Ohio]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Goldfarb|first=Rebecca|title=Helen Hunt Has a Rockin' Start to Her Time Filming in Cleveland|date=22 May 2018|newspaper=[[Cleveland Scene]]|url=https://www.clevescene.com/scene-and-heard/archives/2018/05/22/helen-hunt-has-a-rockin-start-to-her-time-filming-in-cleveland|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wright|first=Matt|title=On the set of \"I See You,\" Helen Hunt movie filming in Northeast Ohio|date=22 May 2018|publisher=[[WJW (TV)]]|url=https://fox8.com/2018/05/22/on-the-set-of-i-see-you-helen-hunt-movie-filming-in-northeast-ohio/|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Extras wanted for Helen Hunt horror movie being filmed in Cleveland area|date=22 May 2018|publisher=[[WJW (TV)]]|url=https://fox8.com/2018/05/22/extras-wanted-for-helen-hunt-horror-movie-being-filmed-in-cleveland-area/|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Grater|first=Tom|title=First look: Helen Hunt horror 'I See You' completes cast, shoot underway (exclusive)|date=14 May 2018|work=[[Screen Daily]]|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/first-look-helen-hunt-horror-i-see-you-completes-cast-shoot-underway-exclusive/5129283.article|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{expand section|date=December 2019}}\nOn review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''I See You'' holds an approval rating of 70%, based on 30 reviews, and an average rating of 5.92/10. The site's consensus reads, \"''I See You'' gets tripped up on its own narrative contortions, but a solid cast and an effective blend of scares and suspense make this slow-building mystery worth watching.\"<ref name=\"rottomatoes\">{{cite web|title=I See You (2019) \u2013 Rotten Tomatoes|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/i_see_you_2019|website=Rotten Tomatoes.com|publisher=Fandango Media|accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 61 out of 100, based on 6 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/i-see-you/critic-reviewss|title=I See You reviews|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nDennis Harvey in ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' described the film as \"an eerie suspense exercise that starts out looking like a supernatural tale \u2014 one of several viewer presumptions this cleverly engineered narrative eventually pulls the rug out from under,\" and added \"strong performances down the line provide psychological credibility to an astute overall package that manages to eke considerable sinister atmosphere from any number of perfectly pleasant locations in the greater Cleveland, Ohio area. A particular plus is William Arcane\u2019s unsettling score.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/i-see-you-review-1203425362/|title=Film Review: \u2018I See You\u2019}}</ref> Stephen Dalton in ''The Hollywood Reporter'' stated, \"''I See You'' is such a finely crafted exercise in slow-burn suspense that its loopy plot contortions only seem absurd in retrospect,\" and elaborated, \"actor turned first-time screenwriter [[Devon Graye]]'s tricksy script keeps audiences on their toes with all this multi-viewpoint misdirection, so much so that most will be caught off-guard by further major reveals. A final shock twist pushes dramatic logic to snapping point, but it does at least wrap up the story on a satisfying crescendo of gothic horror.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/i-see-you-review-1222805|title='I See You': Film Review}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|6079516|I See You (2019)}}\n* {{Metacritic film|i-see-you|I See You (2019)}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|i_see_you_2019|I See You (2019)}}\n*[https://www.paramountmovies.com/movies/i-see-you I See You www.paramountmovies.com]\n\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2019 horror films]]\n[[Category:American crime films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror films]]\n[[Category:American thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about missing people]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Cleveland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{missing information|the film's theatrical/home media releases|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = I See You\n| image          = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = U.S. Theatrical Poster\n| director       = Adam Randall\n| producers      = Matt Waldeck\n| writers        = [[Devon Graye]]\n| story          = \n| starring       = [[Helen Hunt]]<br/>[[Jon Tenney]]<br/>[[Judah Lewis]]<br/>[[Owen Teague]]<br/>[[Libe Barer]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Philipp Blaubach\n| editing        = Jeff Castelluccio\n| studio         = Bankside Films<br>Head Gear Films<br>Quickfire Films<br>Zodiac Features\n| distributor    = [[Saban Films]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|03|11|[[South by Southwest]]|2019|12|6|United States}}\n| runtime        = 96 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''I See You''''' is a 2019 American thriller-horror film written by [[Devon Graye]], directed by [[Adam Randall]], produced by [[Matt Waldeck]] and starring [[Helen Hunt]], [[Jon Tenney]], [[Judah Lewis]], [[Owen Teague]] and [[Libe Barer]].<ref>{{Citation|title=I See You|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6079516/|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Miska|first=Brad|title=Helen Hunt Shoots Off An Intense Look In First Shot From \u2018I See You\u2019|date=14 May 2018|publisher=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3498709/helen-hunt-shoots-off-intense-look-first-shot-see/|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|title=Helen Hunt To Star In Horror-Thriller \u2018I See You\u2019|date=7 June 2017|magazine=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/helen-hunt-i-see-you-horror-movie-casting-1202108848/|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=McNary|first=Dave|title=Helen Hunt to Star in Horror-Thriller \u2018I See You\u2019|date=7 June 2017|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/helen-hunt-i-see-you-1202456735/|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref> It follows a suburban family beset by unexplainable events that may be linked to the recent disappearance of a young boy.\n\n==Plot==\nTen-year-old Justin Whitter is abducted while riding his bicycle through a local park. Greg Harper (Jon Tenney) is made lead detective on the case. Evidence in the form of a green pocket knife is found connecting this case to a previous series of abductions which resulted in the conviction of another man many years prior. Harper's family is shown to be going through its own troubles based on an affair his wife, Jackie ([[Helen Hunt]]), had been in engaged in. Their son, Connor (Judah Lewis), is very resentful toward his mother because of the affair.\n\nMysterious events begin plaguing the house; all the silverware and Jackie's favorite coffee mug go missing, and a window repairman is let in by someone inside the house while the family is away. Jackie's former lover, Todd (Sam Trammel), arrives at the house, and is injured when Jackie's coffee mug falls from the roof and hits him on the head. Jackie hides him in the basement so she can take Connor to school. While looking around the basement, Todd is hit over the head by an unknown assailant and Jackie comes home to find him dead. She panics and assumes that Connor has killed Todd. She and Greg take the body to a wooded area and bury his body, hoping to give Connor an alibi.\n\nConnor is shown footage of \"phrogging\", a practice in which people hide in a house unbeknownst to the owners and move around freely when alone in the house, and is attacked by a figure in a frog mask. Greg and Jackie find Connor tied up in the bathtub with a green pocket knife nearby. Jackie drives Connor to the hospital while Greg searches the house and is attacked with an axe by the frog-masked figure.\n\nThe film then jumps back in time and reveals that the mysterious happenings in the house are caused by two people, Mindy (Libe Barer) and Alec (Owen Teague), who have been \"phrogging\" in the Harper home. Mindy, an experienced phrogger, tries to keep a very low profile so that she never gets caught, while novice phrogger Alec decides he wants to make the family believe they are going insane. Every mysterious occurrence in the film is shown to have been caused by Alec, including the missing silverware and Todd's incapacitation. However, while Todd is in the basement, Mindy witnesses Greg killing him and goes to alert Alec, only to see him incapacitating Connor in the bathtub. She argues with Alec, who mistakenly pushes her down the stairs and knocks her out. Alec hides her in Greg's car. Greg and Jackie find Connor in the bathtub and Jackie takes him to the hospital. After Jackie leaves, Greg takes his own car, taking Mindy with him without realizing it.\n\nMindy awakens in the car and finds a bag of green pocket knives and Justin Whitter's shirt, realizing that Greg is the kidnapper. Greg parks in the forest, where Mindy finds an old trailer with all the abducted children trapped in make-shift closets. As Mindy tries to free them, Greg ambushes her and returns to the house with her. He forces her to stand up before shooting her dead, then doctors the scene to make it appear that she attacked him and he killed her in self-defense. Alec gets Greg's attention and attacks him with an axe. Greg knocks Alec out, but he stirs and takes Greg's gun. Revealing that he knows Greg's identity as the kidnapper, Alec reveals his face to Greg, who appears to recognize him. Greg attempts to explain himself, but Alec makes it clear that he does not care before shooting and killing Greg. Greg's partner Spitzky arrives and shoots Alec, but Alec survives and the two recognize each other. \n\nThe boys are rescued from the trailer and Greg's bags containing the police evidence are found. Jackie and Connor arrive to find their home has become swarmed with police cars and ambulances. Flashbacks are shown of a younger Alec and a friend encountering Greg, who hands Alec a green pocket knife, as in the present day Alec - a previous victim of Greg's - is carried into an ambulance.  This explains why, earlier in the film, that Alec picked that particular house to phrog and begged Mindy to come with him.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Helen Hunt]] as Jackie Harper\n*[[Jon Tenney]] as Greg Harper\n*[[Judah Lewis]] as Connor Harper\n*[[Owen Teague]] as Alec\n*[[Libe Barer]] as Mindy\n*[[Gregory Alan Williams]] as Spitzky\n*[[Erika Alexander]] as Lieutenant Moriah Davis\n*Allison King as Officer Grace Caleb\n*Adam Kern as Window Repairman\n*[[Sam Trammell]] as Todd\n*Jeremy Gladen as Tommy Braun\n*Teri Clark as Mrs. Braun\n*[[Nicole Forester]] as Mrs. Whitter\n\n==Production==\n{{expand section|date=December 2019}}\nPrincipal photography took place in May 2018 in [[Chagrin Falls]], [[Cleveland]] and [[Lakewood, Ohio]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Goldfarb|first=Rebecca|title=Helen Hunt Has a Rockin' Start to Her Time Filming in Cleveland|date=22 May 2018|newspaper=[[Cleveland Scene]]|url=https://www.clevescene.com/scene-and-heard/archives/2018/05/22/helen-hunt-has-a-rockin-start-to-her-time-filming-in-cleveland|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wright|first=Matt|title=On the set of \"I See You,\" Helen Hunt movie filming in Northeast Ohio|date=22 May 2018|publisher=[[WJW (TV)]]|url=https://fox8.com/2018/05/22/on-the-set-of-i-see-you-helen-hunt-movie-filming-in-northeast-ohio/|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Extras wanted for Helen Hunt horror movie being filmed in Cleveland area|date=22 May 2018|publisher=[[WJW (TV)]]|url=https://fox8.com/2018/05/22/extras-wanted-for-helen-hunt-horror-movie-being-filmed-in-cleveland-area/|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Grater|first=Tom|title=First look: Helen Hunt horror 'I See You' completes cast, shoot underway (exclusive)|date=14 May 2018|work=[[Screen Daily]]|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/first-look-helen-hunt-horror-i-see-you-completes-cast-shoot-underway-exclusive/5129283.article|accessdate=9 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{expand section|date=December 2019}}\nOn review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''I See You'' holds an approval rating of 70%, based on 30 reviews, and an average rating of 5.92/10. The site's consensus reads, \"''I See You'' gets tripped up on its own narrative contortions, but a solid cast and an effective blend of scares and suspense make this slow-building mystery worth watching.\"<ref name=\"rottomatoes\">{{cite web|title=I See You (2019) \u2013 Rotten Tomatoes|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/i_see_you_2019|website=Rotten Tomatoes.com|publisher=Fandango Media|accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 61 out of 100, based on 6 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/i-see-you/critic-reviewss|title=I See You reviews|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nDennis Harvey in [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] described the film as \"an eerie suspense exercise that starts out looking like a supernatural tale \u2014 one of several viewer presumptions this cleverly engineered narrative eventually pulls the rug out from under,\" and added \"strong performances down the line provide psychological credibility to an astute overall package that manages to eke considerable sinister atmosphere from any number of perfectly pleasant locations in the greater Cleveland, Ohio area. A particular plus is William Arcane\u2019s unsettling score.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/i-see-you-review-1203425362/|title=Film Review: \u2018I See You\u2019}}</ref> Stephen Dalton in ''The Hollywood Reporter'' stated, \"''I See You'' is such a finely crafted exercise in slow-burn suspense that its loopy plot contortions only seem absurd in retrospect,\" and elaborated, \"actor turned first-time screenwriter [[Devon Graye]]'s tricksy script keeps audiences on their toes with all this multi-viewpoint misdirection, so much so that most will be caught off-guard by further major reveals. A final shock twist pushes dramatic logic to snapping point, but it does at least wrap up the story on a satisfying crescendo of gothic horror.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/i-see-you-review-1222805|title='I See You': Film Review}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|6079516|I See You (2019)}}\n* {{Metacritic film|i-see-you|I See You (2019)}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|i_see_you_2019|I See You (2019)}}\n*[https://www.paramountmovies.com/movies/i-see-you I See You www.paramountmovies.com]\n\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2019 horror films]]\n[[Category:American crime films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror films]]\n[[Category:American thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about missing people]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Cleveland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Ohio]]\n", "name_user": "All Hallow's Wraith", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_See_You_(2019_film)"}
{"title_page": "Udaan (2014 TV series)", "text_new": "{{About|2014 series|1989 series|Udaan (TV series)}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Udaan\n| image                    = Udaan (2014 TV series).jpeg\n| caption                  = <!--Please don't use captions for obvious title cards. See Template:Infobox television instructions-->\n| genre                    = [[Drama]]\n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = \n| developer                = \n| writer                   = [[Robin Bhatt]] <br /> [[Javed Siddiqi]] <br /> [[Sameer Siddiqui]]\n| director                 = \n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = \n| starring                 = {{ubl|[[Spandan Chaturvedi]]|[[Meera Deosthale]]|[[Vijayendra Kumeria]]|[[Vidhi Pandya]]|[[Paras Arora]]|[[Tanya Sharma]]|Gaurav Sareen|[[Toral Rasputra]]}}\n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \"Ye Honslo Ki Udaan Hai\"\n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = India\n| language                 = [[Hindi]]\n| num_seasons              = 1\n| num_episodes             = 1,352\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = Gurudev Bhalla<br>[[Dhaval Gada]]<ref name=\"Bhatt-at-the-launch-of-Udann\">http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/tv/news/Film-maker-Mahesh-Bhatt-at-the-launch of-Udann-in-Delhi/articleshow/40190624.cms</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Film maker Mahesh Bhatt at the launch of Udann in Delhi|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Film-maker-Mahesh-Bhatt-at-the-launch-of-Udann-in-Delhi/articleshow/40190624.cms?|website=Times of India|publisher=Bennett, Coleman and Company LTD|accessdate=7 September 2016}}</ref>\n| producer                 = [[Mahesh Bhatt]]<ref name=\"sai-deodar-comes-back\">{{cite web|url=http://daily.bhaskar.com/news/ENT-TV-interview-after-four-years-gap-sai-deodar-comes-back-on-tv-with-serial-udaan-4714946-NOR.html|title = Interview: After four years of gap, Sai Deodar comes back on TV serial 'Udaan'|work= daily.bhaskar.com|accessdate = 15 September 2014}}</ref>\n| cinematography           = \n| editor                   = \n| camera                   = [[Multi camera]]\n| runtime                  = Approximately 24 minutes\n| company                  = Gurudev Bhalla Productions\n| distributor              = [[Viacom 18]]\n| picture_format           = [[576i]] <br> [[1080i]] [[HDTV]]\n| audio_format             = \n| first_run                = \n| first_aired              = {{start date|df=yes|2014|8|18}}\n| last_aired               = {{end date|df=yes|2019|6|28}}\n| website                  = http://colors.in.com/in/shows/udaan-3652.html\n| production_website       = \n| production_website_title = \n| image_size               = \n| channel                  = [[Colors TV]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://daily.bhaskar.com/news/ENT-watch-udaan-on-colors-1824366.html|title= Watch 'Udaan' on Colors|work= daily.bhaskar.com|accessdate= 15 September 2014}}</ref><!--Parameter is for original language network, not dubs, not reruns.-->\n}}\n\n'''''Udaan''''' ({{Translation}} Flight) is an Indian social drama television series that aired on [[Colors TV]] from 18 August 2014 to 28 June 2019.<ref name=\"bhatt-s-unreleased-film-udaan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-mahesh-bhatt-s-unreleased-film-udaan-becomes-a-tv-show-2010177|title=Mahesh Bhatt's unreleased film 'Udaan' becomes a TV show \u2013 Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|work=dna|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/tv/news/Shastri-Sisters-and-Udann-cast-visit-the-Andhericha-Raja-Pandal/articleshow/41938271.cms|title='Shastri Sisters' and 'Udann' cast visit the Andhericha Raja Pandal \u2013 The Times of India|work=The Times of India|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> From 2014 to 2016, the show starred child actor [[Spandan Chaturvedi]] who played Young Chakor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/television/tv-channels/gecs/colors-to-awaken-rural-masses-with-udaan-140812|title=Colors to awaken rural masses with 'Udaan' \u2013 Indian Television Dot Com|author=Anil Wanvari|publisher=|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref> It then took a generation leap and from 2016 to 2019, the show revolved around Chakor, Suraj, Imli and Vivaan played by [[Meera Deosthale]], [[Vijayendra Kumeria]], [[Vidhi Pandya]] and [[Paras Arora]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/post-leap-vijayendra-kumeria-play-the-male-lead-colors-udann-160128|title=Post leap, Vijayendra Kumeria to play the male lead in Colors' Udann|last=Team|first=Tellychakkar|work=Tellychakkar.com|access-date=2018-08-08|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.iwmbuzz.com/television/celebrities/udann-boyfriend-dont-time-anyone-else-meera-deosthale/2018/02/22|title=Udann is my boyfriend as I don't have time for anyone else: Meera Deosthale {{!}} IWMBuzz|date=2018-02-22|work=IWMBuzz|access-date=2018-08-08|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2019, the show took another leap and focused on Saanvi aka Anjor and Sameer played by [[Tanya Sharma]] and Gaurav Sareen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/television/soaps/story/udaan-take-a-leap-vijayendra-kumeria-meera-deosthale-replaced-by-these-actors-1458247-2019-02-17|title=Udaan to take a leap. Vijayendra Kumeria and Meera Deosthale to be replaced by these actors|website=India Today|language=en}}</ref>\n\n''Udaan'' highlighted the issue of [[bonded labour]] in Indian villages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-i-had-tears-in-my-eyes-when-i-heard-the-script-of-udaan-tv/20140823.htm|title='I had tears in my eyes when I heard the script of Udaan'|date=23 August 2014|work=Rediff|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatvnews.com/entertainment/bollywood/udaan-sapnon-ki-based-on-bonded-labour-16543.html|title=Udaan: Little Chakor becomes bonded labour|publisher=|accessdate=15 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n{{copyedit|section|date=April 2020}}\n{{Update section|date=July 2019}}\n<!--Note: Per WP:TVPLOT, this section should not exceed 500 words.-->\nThe story, set in a village named Azadganj begins in 1996. Kamal Narayan Rajvanshi, a wealthy landlord is the head of Azadganj, who makes the most villagers bonded labourers and keeps them like animals. \n\nAlso living in Azadganj are couple Bhuvan Lal Singh and Kasturi. A pregnant Kasturi is devastated when her father Hariya dies in an accident. Having no money, Bhuvan visits Rajvanshi mansion to beg for money from Kamal.\n\nKamal's wife Tejaswini suggests that they keep the child as collateral instead of money. Kasturi and Bhuvan agree; Kasturi gives birth to a daughter Chakor, on the night of full moon. Tejaswini allows them to take her home for eight years, stating that she must be brought back to the mansion to serve.\n\n===8 years later===\n\nChakor is grown-up as an aspiring Marathon runner, but still kept as a collateral. Kasturi and Bhuvan have another daughter, Imli.chakor goes have haveli for the first time chakor don't want to live there she raised voice for her and the villagers's rights against Kamal. She also maintains a friendship with Kamal's nephew Vivaan.\n\nKamal's son Suraj hates Chakor. After a series of events, it is revealed Chakor has a twin sister Chunni and Kasturi give birth to twin daughters her motherinlaw send chunni to Mumbai. Kamal kills Chunni; Chakor learns about Chunni and vows revenge on Kamal for her death.\n\nChakor's Marathon coach Arjun Khanna falls in love with Kamal's daughter Bhagya. The two espace and soon marry. Soon, Chakor leaves Azadganj with Arjun and Bhagya to pursue her dreams but vows to return after ten years, whereas Kamal buries her grandmother Savitri alive.\n\n===15 years later===\n\nChakor makes a comeback, having become a Marathon runner just like she dreamt and desired. She discovers about Savitri's death and gets Kamal arrested though he is later released. Imli is shown to be hating Chakor for her disappearance.\n\nVivaan is an angered man after his father Manohar's death and Kamal married Manohar's wife Ranjana, who is later revealed to have killed Manohar herself to marry Kamal. Suraj is just like and works for Kamal. He often clashes with Chakor.\n\nSoon, Vivaan finds out Ranjana murdered Manohar and severs his ties with her. Though at first, he behaves rudely towards Chakor, their childhood bond slowly revives and they begin to fall in love. Imli begins falling for Suraj and gets pregnant with his child.\n\nSuraj's marriage is arranged to Chakor's co-Marathon runner Tina Raichand. Chakor-Vivaan and Tina-Suraj's wedding is fixed on the same day. Imli accepts Chakor and reveals about her pregnancy. They tell the situation to Tina who accepts their plan not wanting to marry too.\n\nVivaan joins them also. On the wedding, Imli wears Tina's marriage clothes as Tina runs away according to the plan. Suraj learns about this and replaces the brides and grooms with wrong. Due to this, mistakenly Chakor marries Suraj while Vivaan marries Imli. Imli and Vivaan blame Chakor for it Suraj mistreat chakor and blackmail chakor that if she give him the divorce he give that knife to police have imli fingerprint from which he used to murder kamalnaryan meanwhile imli fallen in love with vivan she tell chakor about her feelings chakor with big heart give imli her blessings and also vivan fallen in love with imli imli had a miscarriage \n\n\n\nKamal makes Suraj a labourer and mistreats him, but he is rescued by Chakor and Kamal's mistreating backfires. As Chakor and Suraj's relation becomes strong, they are unable to live without each other. On their first anniversary, Suraj expresses to Chakor he loves her and Chakor realises she loves him too. They decide to start a new life.\n\nElsewhere, Imli tells she is pregnant again but Vivaan is disappointed because of being told in his being a father reports that he can't be a father ever. He starts believing Imli is carrying Suraj's child again. To save Imli, Suraj tells everyone he is her child's father.\n\nChakor, after hearing all this leaves the Rajvanshi mansion and divorces Suraj. It is later revealed that Vivaan's doctor lied about the reports on Ragini's orders. The truth is finally out and Ragini escapes. Imli forgives Vivaan and Chakor apologizes to Suraj; they reunite.\n\nImli miscarries again but doesn't reveal to anyone. Vivaan discovers this and blames her. Imli misunderstands it was Chakor who revealed her miscarriage to Vivaan. She gives a sleeping injection to Vivaan who slips into coma. Now detesting Chakor, she joins hands with Kamal; they stab and throw Chakor in a river with help from goons.\n\n===1 month later===\n\nAs the river reaches [[Varanasi]], Chakor is shown to be saved by a priest, living with him in his house. A doctor reveals that Chakor is pregnant. Brainwashed by Imli, Suraj believes Chakor left him. Chakor contacts Imli who tells her Suraj wants to kill her so she do not return to Azadganj.\n\nLater, Chakor is asked and shifted to live in Ranvijay Singh's house. Ranvijay is an inspector vowing to avenge his father Rajan's death from Rajan's business rival by killing the businessman's son. Suraj visits Varanasi; he and Chakor meet and sort out all things, wanting answers from Imli.\n\nChakor finds out Rajan's business rival is Kamal and Ranvijay is vowing to kill Suraj. She tells Suraj. Ranvijay sees them and realises he wants to kill Suraj. He kidnaps him and tries to forcefully marry Chakor, but they get him arrested and return to Azadganj.\n\nImli tells them that she lied to save them from Kamal, and they forgive her. Kamal kidnaps and pushes Chakor resulting her to fall and thus losing her baby. To avenge for it, Chakor kills Kamal thus also avenging Chunni and Savitri's deaths and making Azadganj independent, but is jailed for 5 years.\n\n===5 years later===\n\nChakor gets released and firstly meets Kasturi, Bhuvan and the villagers. She then visits the Rajvanshi mansion, and learns all of Imli's misdeeds. It is discovered that Imli helped Ranvijay to escape and married him, who hit Suraj on his head leading Suraj to lose his memory, and they appointed him as their servant.\n\nImli is now the head of Azadganj, mistreating the villagers just like Kamal. Tejaswini is being locked by Imli in a secret room of Rajvanshi mansion, while Vivaan is still in coma. Suraj recalls everything and unites with Chakor; they free Tejaswini and go to punish Imli, who shoots Ranvijay to death and escapes. Azadganj gets independence again.\n\n===2 years later===\n\nChakor and Suraj live happily with their family and have a daughter named Saanvi. They start a business, and become rivals with Karan Oberoi, a successful business tycoon. Imli returns to have labouring back in Azadganj and joins hands with the antagonistic Karan to destroy Chakor.\n\nLater, Karan dies in an accident, whereas Imli gets exposed as Vivaan wakes up from coma. He has her arrested. Eventually, she is released. Imli's former gun dealer Colonel Yashwant Bedi tries to kill Suraj for a lie. Chakor is about to shoot him to stop him but Vivaan comes in between and dies. Yashwant is arrested. \n\nImli swears revenge for Vivaan's death and kidnaps Saanvi. Imli's goons throw a doll whose size is that of Saanvi in a river, due to which everyone presume Saanvi dead. Suraj blames Chakor for it and severes all ties with her. Chakor, Kasturi and Bhuvan leave Azadganj, while Imli makes Saanvi labourer and hands her to an Azadganj new couple.\n\n===7 years later===\n\nChakor, Kasturi and Bhuvan reside in [[Mumbai]]. Saanvi is being raised by the same couple Sugna and Kesho. She is known in Azadganj with the name of Anjor. Chakor returns to Azadganj for some work. Some goons kidnap Saanvi but Chakor rescues her by defeating them. The two begin to share a friendship, unaware of their relation.Suraj also come back azadganj and meet anjor soon Suraj and chakor find out that anjor is their daughter saanvi and anjor also accept Suraj and chakor\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Spandan Chaturvedi]] as young Chakor Singh (2014\u201316)/ young Chunni: Kasturi and Bhuvan's daughter; Chakor and Imli's sister (2015; dead)\n* [[Meera Deosthale]]/[[Toral Rasputra]] as Chakor Rajvanshi: Kasturi and Bhuvan's daughter; Chunni and Imli's sister; Vivaan's former fianc\u00e9e; Suraj's wife; Anjor's mother (2016\u201319)/(2019)\n* Apurva Jyotir/Darshan Gujrar as young Suraj Rajvanshi (2014\u201315)/(2015\u201316)\n* [[Vijayendra Kumeria]] as Suraj Rajvanshi: Tejaswini and Kamal's son; Bhagya and Ragini's brother; Tina's former fianc\u00e9; Chakor's husband; Anjor's father (2016\u201318; dead)/Raghav Khanna: Suraj's doppelganger (2018\u201319; dead)\n* Tasheen Shah as young Imli Singh (2014\u201316)\n* [[Vidhi Pandya]] as Imli Singh/ Archana: Kasturi and Bhuvan's daughter; Chakor and Chunni's sister; Vivaan and Ranvijay's former wife (2016\u201318, 2018\u201319; dead)\n* Wahib Kapadia as young Vivaan Rajvanshi (2014\u201316)\n* [[Paras Arora]] as Vivaan Rajvanshi: Ranjana and Manohar's son; Chakor's former fianc\u00e9; Imli's former husband (2016\u201318; dead)\n* Aadhya Barot/Samriddhi Yadav as young Saanvi \"Anjor\" Rajvanshi (2018)/(2018\u201319)\n* [[Tanya Sharma]] as Saanvi \"Anjor\" Sharma: Chakor and Suraj's daughter; Sameer's wife (2019)\n* Gaurav Sareen as Sameer Sharma: Jaya and Manoj's son; Vanshika's brother; Anjor's husband (2019; dead)\n* [[Vikas Bhalla]] as ACP Ranvijay Singh: Malini and Rajan's son; Preeti and Kavya's brother; Imli's former husband (2017, 2017\u201318, 2019)\n* [[Mohammad Nazim]] as Gumaan Singh Rajvanshi: Bharat's son; Sandesh, Mahendra and Vaani's brother; Garima's husband; Rohan's father (2018)\n* [[Rishina Kandhari]] 